bibliography.abstract: This report lists only those literature sources having direct applicability to the Lake Mead National Recreation Area.  The location of unpublished reports is given where appropriate.  In most instances, these reports are available at the University of Nevada Las Vegas library, or in the files at Lake Mead National Recreation Area.  The species accounts and locality data are compiled exclusively from the literature, and do not contain the extensive and detailed collections the authors have made since 1974.  The rationale for compiling the species accounts in this manner was so that other researchers can better tell which sources are worthy of their attention.

bibliography.title: GOGA_2014BioBlitz_iNaturalist_SENSITIVE
bibliography.abstract: Location data in iNaturalist can be obscured for the following reasons: 1) the observer obscured the record- this sets a location point up to 10km off true. 2) the observer sets the record to private- no-one can see the true location except the observer. 3) iNaturalist obscures the record automatically for sensitive species, by up to 10km from true. This dataset shows the true coordinate values (as added by the observer into iNaturalist) for nearly all the observations made during the 2014 GGNRA BioBlitz using iNaturalistFor this dataset, the true location was able to be obtained via the BioBlitz project administrator whom can see true coordinates for any record that had been added to the BioBlitz project, regardless of whether iNaturalist or the observer had set it to obscure. The few records that show outside the boundary of GOGA had either been set to private, or had not been added to the project, and I was not able to extract true coordinates.Data were collected on March 28-29, 2014 and downloaded from iNaturalist.org on January 22, 2016. This dataset was reprojected from the original WGS84 to NAD 1983 UTM zone 10. Datum, D_North_America_1983
bibliography.purpose: This dataset is intended to allow internal NPS staff to see coordinate data for all species found during the 2014 Golden Gate National Recreation Area (GGNRA) BioBlitz that was recorded using iNaturalist platform, and downloaded from iNaturalist on Jan 22nd 2015. It contains coordinate data for sensitive species as well as non-sensitive species.

citation: Stephens JL. 2017. Landbird monitoring: 2016 results from Crater Lake National Park and Oregon Caves National Monument and Preserve. Natural Resource Data Series. NPS/KLMN/NRDS—2017/1113. National Park Service. Fort Collins, Colorado

bibliography.title: Landbird monitoring: 2016 results from Crater Lake National Park and Oregon Caves National Monument and Preserve
bibliography.abstract: In 2016, the Klamath Inventory and Monitoring Network (KLMN) of the National Park Service implemented the ninth year of their long-term landbird monitoring protocol. Klamath Bird Observatory, in partnership with the KLMN, developed the protocol and completed this ninth year effort. Multiple standard avian sampling methods were implemented, including variable circular plot point counts, area search surveys, mist netting, species checklists, and habitat surveys. In 2016, a third year of point counts were completed, along with corresponding species checklists and habitat surveys, at 35 locations within Crater Lake National Park and four locations within Oregon Caves National Monument and Preserve. The operation of an ongoing constant effort monitoring station, which included mist netting, point counts, area searches, species checklists, and habitat surveys, continued at Oregon Caves National Monument and Preserve during the breeding and fall migration seasons. Relative abundance (birds/station), as measured by point count and area search methods, was calculated for all survey sites combined within each park. Total captures, by season, were calculated using constant effort mist netting data. Species of conservation importance were among the most abundant species at each park. Results are presented along with conservation status of individual species based on Partners in Flight state and continental plans and Oregon and California Wildlife Conservation Strategies. This ninth year of implementation of the KLMN landbird monitoring program continued to lay the groundwork for improved understanding of landbird status and long-term trends in each park. When analyzed in the framework of the Klamath Bird Monitoring Network, the contribution of KLMN parks to bird conservation in this region will help inform landbird conservation in the West.
